<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-03-19T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-03-19T23:00:00-05:00" n="247" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d247">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/6071: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Tientsin (<persName type="from">Lockhart</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tientsin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-03-20T12:00:00+08:00">March 20,
                                1933—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received March 20—4:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>General Yao Tung-fang has relieved General Ho Chu-kuo as commanding
                            officer in Chinwangtao area. General Ho and his troops, who have been at
                            Chinwangtao for several months, are being moved to Lwanchow.</p>
                        <p>General Han Fu-chu passed through Tientsin yesterday from Shantung to
                            Peiping en route Paotingfu for conference with Chiang Kai-shek.
                            Unconfirmed reports have been current for several days that Han may
                            assume command of Chiang’s forces in North China in the near future.</p>
                        <p>Both sides still claiming Hsifengkou.</p>
                        <p>Situation Tientsin quiet.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>